flagÂ¶

Flag emoji for Python.

Converts flag emoji to ASCII and other way round.

Source on Github

This is based on http://schinckel.net/2015/10/29/unicode-flags-in-python/ by schinckel

ExampleÂ¶

>>> import flag

>>> flag.flagize("Flag of Israel :IL:")
'Flag of Israel ðŸ‡®ðŸ‡±'

>>> flag.dflagize(u"Flag of Israel ðŸ‡®ðŸ‡±")
'Flag of Israel :IL:'

InstallÂ¶

pip install emoji-country-flag

See: https://pypi.org/project/emoji-country-flag/

How it worksÂ¶

All the flag emoji are actually composed of two unicode letters. These are the 26 regional indicator symbols.

Alone they look like this: ðŸ‡¦ ðŸ‡§ ðŸ‡¨ ðŸ‡© ðŸ‡ª ðŸ‡« ðŸ‡¬ ðŸ‡­ ðŸ‡® ðŸ‡¯ ðŸ‡° ðŸ‡± ðŸ‡² ðŸ‡³ ðŸ‡´ ðŸ‡µ ðŸ‡¶ ðŸ‡· ðŸ‡¸ ðŸ‡¹ ðŸ‡º ðŸ‡» ðŸ‡¼ ðŸ‡½ ðŸ‡¾ ðŸ‡¿

If you pair them up according to ISO 3166 some browsers and phones will display a flag. For example CZ is Czechia: ðŸ‡¨ + ðŸ‡¿ = ðŸ‡¨ðŸ‡¿

So, to encode an ASCII code like :NR: to ðŸ‡³ðŸ‡·, we just need to convert the ASCII N and R to the corresponding regional indicator symbols ðŸ‡³ and ðŸ‡·. To reverse it, we translate the regional indicator symbols back to ASCII letters.
